## Sampling Frame

The research uses a 2D sampling matrix: 6 adoption-status rows × 5 context-segment columns.

| Row | Adoption Status | Description |
|-----|----------------|-------------|
| 1 | adopter | Currently uses the product regularly |
| 2 | partial-adopter | Uses it but inconsistently or for limited use cases |
| 3 | abandoner | Tried it, used it, then stopped |
| 4 | evaluated-and-rejected | Evaluated it seriously but chose not to adopt |
| 5 | never-tried-aware | Aware of it but has never tried |
| 6 | actively-anti | Actively advises others against it |

| Column | Context Segment |
|--------|----------------|
| A | B2B-small (1-50 employees) |
| B | B2B-mid (51-500 employees) |
| C | B2B-large-regulated (500+ or regulated industry) |
| D | B2C-high-autonomy (solo decision-maker) |
| E | B2C-low-autonomy (requires others' buy-in) |

**Row-count requirements:**
- Rows 3, 4, 6 (abandoner, evaluated-and-rejected, actively-anti): **minimum 2 subjects each**
- Rows 1, 2, 5: minimum 1 subject each

Abandoners and refusers are structurally required — they answer adoption-friction questions that adopters cannot.
